COG250Y1-Y-20179.courseTitle: Introduction to Cognitive Science (formerly JUP250Y1, UNI250Y1)
COG250Y1-Y-20179.courseDescription: An introduction to the problems, theories and research [strategies central to the interdisciplinary field focusing on the nature and organization of the human mind and other cognitive systems. Interrelations among the philosophical, psychological, linguistic and computer science aspects of the field are emphasized.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

COG341H1-F-20179.courseTitle: Issues on Attention, Perception and Consciousness
COG341H1-F-20179.courseDescription: An examination of core topics in cognitive science building on introductions in COG250Y. Typical topics include: perception and attention; concepts; imagery; consciousness.

COG342H1-S-20179.courseTitle: Issues on Concepts, Theories of Mind, Cognitive Evolution
COG342H1-S-20179.courseDescription: An examination of core topics in cognitive science building on introductions in COG250Y. Typical topics include: concepts; theories of mind; cognitive evolution.

COG401H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Advanced treatment of cognitive science topics.
COG401H1-F-20179.prerequisite: 5.0 credits in courses listed in the cognitive science major.

COG401H1-S-20179.courseDescription: Advanced treatment of cognitive science topics.
COG401H1-S-20179.prerequisite: 5.0 credits in courses listed in the cognitive science major.

COG402H1-F-20179.prerequisite: 5.0 credits in courses listed in the cognitive science major.

COG403H1-S-20179.courseDescription: The role of Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning in the design and construction of cognitive systems and their role within Cognitive Science. Topics may vary from year to year, but may include deep learning, neural networks, knowledge representation and reasoning, and computational Neuroscience.
COG403H1-S-20179.prerequisite: COG250Y1, CSC148H1, CSC384H1 (requires permission of the Cognitive Science director), (MAT135H1, MAT136H1)/MAT137Y1, PHL342H1, PSY473H1/PSY493H1, 0.5 FCE in statistics

COG415H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course provides COG students with the opportunities to practice quantitative and qualitative evaluation and assessment methods in real world situations and juxtapose theory with practice. Placement activities will ground topics such as problem solving, logistics, decision making, etc., through practical application, individual and group / in-class critical reflection.
